A study in Portugal revealed that 83.4% of teenage girls received contraceptive information at school.
However, 16% of sexually active girls aged 15-19 do not use any birth control.
Nearly one-third have used the morning-after pill.
The pill, containing levonorgestrel, prevents pregnancy by inhibiting ovulation.
Despite controversy, experts argue that easy access to emergency contraception can reduce teen pregnancies.
The FDA debates making the morning-after pill available without a prescription.
Meanwhile, some states allow pharmacists to refuse filling birth control prescriptions.
